description: Borrowed from Medieval Latin populātus, past participle of populor (“populate”), from Latin populus (“people”).

adjectives.description: populate (comparative more populate, superlative most populate)

verbs.description: populate (third-person singular simple present populates, present participle populating, simple past and past participle populated)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To supply with inhabitants; to people.
(intransitive) To increase in number; to breed.
(computing, transitive, intransitive) To fill initially empty items in a collection.
examples: John clicked the Search button and waited for the list to populate.
Clicking the refresh button will populate the grid.

entries.meaning: (electronics) To fill initially empty slots or sockets on a circuit board or similar.
